# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: betel
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:betel/3-carene] A colorless liquid, it is not water-soluble, but miscible with fats and oils.
[src:betel/3-carene] It is chiral, occurring naturally both as the racemate and enantio-enriched forms.
[src:betel/3-carene] Treatment with peracetic acid gives 3,4-caranediol.
[src:betel/3-carene] Pyrolysis over ferric oxide induces rearrangement, giving *p*-cymene.
[src:betel/3-carene] Carene is used in the perfume industry and as a chemical intermediate.
[src:betel/3-carene] Because carene can be found in cannabis naturally, it can also be found in cannabis distillates.
[src:betel/3-carene] Greater concentrations of carene in a distillate give it an earthier taste and smell.
[src:betel/3-carene] 3-Carene is also present in mango, giving the fruit a characteristic pine-like flavor and aroma.
[src:betel/akpeteshie] It is popular throughout West Africa, and goes by many names including **apio**, **ogoglo**, **ogogoro** (**Ogog'**), **VC10,** **Kill Me Quick**, **Efie Nipa, Kele, Kumepreko, Anferewoase, Apiatiti, Home Boy, Nana Drobo, One Touch** among others.
[src:betel/akpeteshie] It is also known as sapele water, kparaga, kai-kai, Sun gbalaja, egun inu igo meaning *The Masquerade in the Bottle*, push-me-push-you, and/or crim-kena, sonsé ("do you do it?" in Yoruba language).
[src:betel/akpeteshie] In the Igbo language it is known as *Akpuru achia*.
[src:betel/akpeteshie] Other Nigerian epithets include: *Udi Ogagan*, *Agbagba* Urhobo, as well *OHMS* (Our Home Made Stuff), *Iced Water*, *Push Me, I Push You* and *Craze man in the bottle*.
[src:betel/akpeteshie] Ghanaian moonshine is referred to as akpeteshie.
[src:betel/akpeteshie] With British colonization of what became known as the Gold Coast, such local brewing was outlawed in the early 1930s.
[src:betel/akpeteshie] Dotse about his life under British colonial rule: "Our contention was that the drink the white man brought is the same as ours.
[src:betel/akpeteshie] The white men's contention was that ours was too strong...Before the white men came we were using akpeteshie.
[src:betel/akpeteshie] But when they came they banned it, probably because they wanted to make sales on their own liquor.
[src:betel/akpeteshie] When you had a visitor whom you knew very well, then you ordered that kpótomenui be brought.
[src:betel/akpeteshie] The name "akpeteshie" was given to the drink with its prohibition: the word comes from the Ga language (*ape te shie*, the act of hiding) spoken in greater Accra and means *they are hiding*, referring to the secretive way in which non-European inhabitants were forced to consume the beverage.
[src:betel/akpeteshie] Despite being outlawed, illicit spirits remained commonplace, with reports that even schoolboys were able to easily obtain akpeteshie through the 1930s.
[src:betel/akpeteshie] Demand for akpeteshie and the profits to be made from its sale was enough to encourage the spread of sugar cane cultivation in the Anlo region of Ghana.
[src:betel/akpeteshie] Distillation was legalized with decolonization and Ghanaian independence.
[src:betel/akpeteshie] The first factory was established in the Volta Region, taking advantage of the area's supply of sugar cane plantations.
[src:betel/akpeteshie] Ogogoro is distilled from the juice of Raffia palm trees.
[src:betel/akpeteshie] An incision is made in the trunk and a gourd placed outside it for collection, which is collected a day or two later.
[src:betel/akpeteshie] After extraction, the sap is boiled to form steam, which subsequently condenses and is collected for consumption.
[src:betel/akpeteshie] Akpeteshie is distilled from palm wine or sugarcane juice.
[src:betel/akpeteshie] This sweetened liquid or wine is first fermented in a large barrels, sometimes with the help of yeast.
[src:betel/akpeteshie] After this first stage of fermentation, fires are built under the barrels in order to bring the liquid to a boil and pass the resulting vapor through a copper pipe within cooling barrels, where it condenses and drips into sieved jars.
[src:betel/akpeteshie] The boiled juice then undergoes a distillation.
[src:betel/akpeteshie] The resulting spirit is between 40 and 50% alcohol by volume.
[src:betel/akpeteshie] Akpeteshie is not professionally bottled or sealed, but instead poured into unlabeled used bottles.
[src:betel/akpeteshie] The spirit can be bought wholesale from a brewer or by the glass at boutiques and bars.
[src:betel/akpeteshie] Although not professionally advertised, the drink is very popular.
[src:betel/akpeteshie] This is partially due to its price, which is lower than that of other professionally bottled or imported drinks.
[src:betel/akpeteshie] Its relative cheapness makes it a drink associated more with the poor, but even those who can afford better quality are said to consume the spirit in secret.
[src:betel/akpeteshie] The potency of the liquor heavily affects the bodily senses, providing a feeling likened to that of a knockout punch.
[src:betel/akpeteshie] Practiced drinkers can be seen acknowledging receipt by blowing out air or pounding their chest.
[src:betel/akpeteshie] As drink and commodity, respectively, ogogoro carries substantial cultural and economic significance within Nigeria.
[src:betel/akpeteshie] It is an essential part of numerous religious and social ceremonies; Burutu (Ijaw) priests pour it onto the ground as offerings to contact their gods, while fathers of Nigerian brides use it as a libation by which they provide their official blessing to a wedding.
[src:betel/akpeteshie] The economic facets of ogogoro have been equally salient throughout recent Nigerian history.
[src:betel/akpeteshie] Many poor Nigerian families homebrew the drink as a means of economic subsistence, many of whom sell shots of it on city street corners.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] The natural cause is the presence of soil minerals producing sodium carbonate (Na2CO3) and sodium bicarbonate (NaHCO3) upon weathering.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] Coal-fired boilers / power plants, when using coal or lignite rich in limestone, produce ash containing calcium oxide.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] CaO readily dissolves in water to form slaked lime, Ca(OH)2, and carried by rain water to rivers / irrigation water.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] Lime softening process precipitates Ca2+ and Mg2+ ions / removes hardness in the water and also converts sodium bicarbonates in river water into sodium carbonate.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] Sodium carbonates (washing soda) further reacts with the remaining Ca2+ and Mg2+ in the water to remove / precipitate the total hardness.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] Also water-soluble sodium salts present in the ash enhance the sodium content in water.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] The global coal consumption in the world was 7.7 billion tons in the year 2011.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] Thus river water is made devoid of Ca2+ and Mg2+ ions and enhanced Na+ by coal-fired boilers.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] Many sodium salts are used in industrial and domestic applications such as sodium carbonate, sodium bicarbonate (baking soda), sodium sulphate, sodium hydroxide (caustic soda), sodium hypochlorite (bleaching powder), etc. in huge quantities.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] These salts are mainly produced from sodium chloride (common salt).
[src:betel/alkali-soil] All the sodium in these salts enter into the river / ground water during their production process or consumption enhancing water sodicity.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] The total global consumption of sodium chloride is 270 million tons in the year 2010.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] This is nearly equal to the salt load in the mighty Amazon River.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] Man made sodium salts contribution is nearly 7% of total salt load of all the rivers.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] Sodium salt load problem aggravates in the downstream of intensively cultivated river basins located in China, India, Egypt, Pakistan, west Asia, Australia, western US, etc. due to accumulation of salts in the remaining water after meeting various transpiration and evaporation losses.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] Another source of man-made sodium salts addition to the agriculture fields / land mass is in the vicinity of the wet cooling towers using sea water to dissipate waste heat generated in various industries located near the sea coast.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] Huge capacity cooling towers are installed in oil refineries, petrochemical complexes, fertilizer plants, chemical plants, nuclear & thermal power stations, centralized HVAC systems, etc.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] The drift / fine droplets emitted from the cooling towers contain nearly 6% sodium chloride which would deposit on the vicinity areas.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] This problem aggravates where the national pollution control norms are not imposed or not implemented to minimize the drift emissions to the best industrial norm for the sea water based wet cooling towers.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] The man-made cause is the application of softened water in irrigation (surface or ground water) containing relatively high proportion of sodium bicarbonates and less calcium and magnesium.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] Alkaline soils are difficult to take into agricultural production.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] Due to the low infiltration capacity, rain water stagnates on the soil easily and, in dry periods, cultivation is hardly possible without copious irrigated water and good drainage.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] Agriculture is limited to crops tolerant to surface waterlogging (e.g. rice, grass) and the productivity is lower.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] Soil alkalinity is associated with the presence of sodium carbonate (Na2CO3) or sodium bicarbonate (NaHCO3) in the soil, either as a result of natural weathering of the soil particles or brought in by irrigation and/or flood water.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] See carbonate for the equilibrium of carbonate-bicarbonate-carbon dioxide.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] The above reactions are similar to the dissolution of calcium carbonate, the solubility of the two salts being the only difference.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] H2CO3 (carbonic acid) is unstable and produces H2O (water) and CO2 (carbon dioxide gas, escaping into the atmosphere).
[src:betel/alkali-soil] This explains the remaining alkalinity (or rather basicity) in the form of soluble sodium hydroxide and the high pH or low pOH.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] Not all the dissolved sodium carbonate undergoes the above chemical reaction.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] The remaining sodium carbonate, and hence the presence of CO2− 3 ions, causes CaCO3 (which is only slightly soluble) to precipitate as solid calcium carbonate (limestone), because the product of the CO2− 3 concentration and the Ca2+ concentration exceeds the allowable limit.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] Hence, the calcium ions Ca2+ are immobilized.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] Na+ is more mobile and has a smaller electric charge than Ca2+ so that the thickness of the DDL increases as more sodium ions occupy it.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] The DDL thickness is also influenced by the total concentration of ions in the soil moisture in the sense that higher concentrations cause the DDL zone to shrink.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] Clay particles with considerable ESP (> 16), in contact with non-saline soil moisture have an expanded DDL zone and the soil swells (dispersion).
[src:betel/alkali-soil] The phenomenon results in deterioration of the soil structure, and especially crust formation and compaction of the top layer.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] Hence the infiltration capacity of the soil and the water availability in the soil is reduced, whereas the surface-water-logging or surface runoff is increased.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] Seedling emergence and crop production are badly affected.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] Alkalinity problems are more pronounced in clay soils than in loamy, silty or sandy soils.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] The clay soils containing montmorillonite or smectite (swelling clays) are more subject to alkalinity problems than illite or kaolinite clay soils.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] The reason is that the former types of clay have larger specific surface areas (*i.e.* the surface area of the soil particles divided by their volume) and higher cation exchange capacity (CEC).
[src:betel/alkali-soil] The residual sodium carbonate (RSC, meq/L): The formula for calculating the residual sodium carbonate is: RSC= [HCO− 3 + CO2− 3] − [Ca2+ + Mg2+] = {HCO− 3/61 + CO2− 3/30} − {Ca2+/20 + Mg2+/12} which must not be much higher than 1 and preferably less than 0.5.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] The above expression recognizes the presence of bicarbonates (HCO− 3), the form in which most carbonates are dissolved.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] While calculating SAR and RSC, the water quality present at the root zone of the crop should be considered which would take into account the leaching factor in the field.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] The partial pressure of dissolved CO2 at the plants root zone also decides the calcium present in dissolved form in the field water.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] USDA follows the adjusted SAR for calculating water sodicity.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] Many times salts' migration to the top soil takes place from the underground water sources rather than surface sources.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] Where the underground water table is high and the land is subjected to high solar radiation, ground water oozes to the land surface due to capillary action and gets evaporated leaving the dissolved salts in the top layer of the soil.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] Where the underground water contains high salts, it leads to acute salinity problem.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] This problem can be reduced by applying mulch to the land.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] Using poly-houses or shade netting during summer for cultivating vegetables/crops is also advised to mitigate soil salinity and conserve water / soil moisture.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] Poly-houses filter the intense summer solar radiation in tropical countries to save the plants from water stress and leaf burns.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] Where the ground water quality is not alkaline / saline and ground water table is high, salts build up in the soil can be averted by using the land throughout the year for growing plantation trees / permanent crops with the help of lift irrigation.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] When the ground water is used at required leaching factor, the salts in the soil would not build up.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] Plowing the field soon after cutting the crop is also advised to prevent salt migration to the top soil and conserve the soil moisture during the intense summer months.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] This is done to break the capillary pores in the soil to prevent water reaching the surface of the soil.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] Clay soils in high annual rain fall (more than 100 cm) areas do not generally suffer from high alkalinity as the rain water runoff is able to reduce/leach the soil salts to comfortable levels if proper rainwater harvesting methods are followed.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] In some agricultural areas, the use of subsurface "tile lines" are used to facilitate drainage and leach salts.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] Continuous drip irrigation would lead to alkali soils formation in the absence of leaching / drainage water from the field.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] It is also possible to reclaim alkaline soils by adding acidifying minerals like pyrite or cheaper alum or aluminium sulfate.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] Alternatively, gypsum (calcium sulfate, CaSO 4 · 2 H 2O) can also be applied as a source of Ca2+ ions to replace the sodium at the exchange complex.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] Gypsum also reacts with sodium carbonate to convert into sodium sulphate which is a neutral salt and does not contribute to high pH.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] There must be enough natural drainage to the underground, or else an artificial subsurface drainage system must be present, to permit leaching of the excess sodium by percolation of rain and/or irrigation water through the soil profile.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] Calcium chloride is also used to reclaim alkali soils.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] CaCl2 converts Na2CO3 into NaCl precipitating CaCO3.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] Calcium nitrate has a similar effect, with NaNO3 in the leachate.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] Spent acid (HCl, H2SO4, etc.) can also be used to reduce the excess Na2CO3 in the soil/water.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] Where urea is made available cheaply to farmers, it is also used to reduce the soil alkalinity / salinity primarily.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] The ammonium (NH+ 4) cation produced by urea hydrolysis which is a strongly sorbing cation exchanges with the weakly sorbing Na+ cation from the soil structure and Na+ is released into water.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] Thus alkali soils adsorb / consume more urea compared to other soils.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] To reclaim the soils completely one needs prohibitively high doses of amendments.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] Most efforts are therefore directed to improving the top layer only (say the first 10 cm of the soils), as the top layer is most sensitive to deterioration of the soil structure.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] The treatments, however, need to be repeated in a few (say 5) years' time.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] It is difficult to survive in alkali soils for the trees with deeper rooting system which can be more than 60 meters deep in good non-alkali soils.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] It will be important to refrain from irrigation (ground water or surface water) with poor quality water.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] In viticulture, adding naturally occurring chelating agents such as tartaric acid to irrigation water has been suggested, to solubilize calcium and magnesium carbonates in sodic soils.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] One way of reducing sodium carbonate is to cultivate glasswort or saltwort or barilla plants.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] These plants sequester the sodium carbonate they absorb from alkali soil into their tissues.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] The ash of these plants contains good quantity of sodium carbonate which can be commercially extracted and used in place of sodium carbonate derived from common salt which is highly energy intensive process.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] Thus alkali lands deterioration can be checked by cultivating barilla plants which can serve as food source, biomass fuel and raw material for soda ash and potash, etc.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] Saline soils are mostly also sodic (the predominant salt is sodium chloride), but they do not have a very high pH nor a poor infiltration rate.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] Upon leaching they are usually not converted into a (sodic) alkali soil as the Na+ ions are easily removed.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] Therefore, saline (sodic) soils mostly do not need gypsum applications for their reclamation.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] Since the 1990s, research and experimentation have been conducted in China and elsewhere for remediation and utilization of alkali land via combined agriculture and aquaculture practices, with considerable success and gains in experience.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] Despite technical, infrastructure and management challenges, aquaculture technology of utilizing inland saline-alkali water and non-arable land for seafood production is becoming mature, covering wide range of seafood species including shrimps, crabs, shellfish and fish such as sea bass and grouper.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] In recent years, aquaculture (or *salt-alkali land aquaculture*) has been recommended by the Ministry of Agriculture and Rural Affairs of China as an economically viable and environmentally beneficial model for the transformation and utilization of saline-alkali land.
[src:betel/alkali-soil] FAO noted in a recent newsletter that alkaline land is one area that there are innovative ways and opportunities for aquaculture to expand.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Alkaloids are produced by a large variety of organisms including bacteria, fungi, plants, and animals.
[src:betel/alkaloids] They can be purified from crude extracts of these organisms by acid-base extraction, or solvent extractions followed by silica-gel column chromatography.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Many have found use in traditional or modern medicine, or as starting points for drug discovery.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Other alkaloids possess psychotropic (e.g. psilocin) and stimulant activities (e.g. cocaine, caffeine, nicotine, theobromine), and have been used in entheogenic rituals or as recreational drugs.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Alkaloids can be toxic (e.g. atropine, tubocurarine).
[src:betel/alkaloids] Although alkaloids act on a diversity of metabolic systems in humans and other animals, they almost uniformly evoke a bitter taste.
[src:betel/alkaloids] The boundary between alkaloids and other nitrogen-containing natural compounds is not clear-cut.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Most alkaloids are basic, although some have neutral and even weakly acidic properties.
[src:betel/alkaloids] In addition to carbon, hydrogen and nitrogen, alkaloids may also contain oxygen or sulfur.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Rarer still, they may contain elements such as phosphorus, chlorine, and bromine.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Compounds like amino acid peptides, proteins, nucleotides, nucleic acid, amines, and antibiotics are usually not called alkaloids.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Natural compounds containing nitrogen in the exocyclic position (mescaline, serotonin, dopamine, etc.) are usually classified as amines rather than as alkaloids.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Some authors, however, consider alkaloids a special case of amines.
[src:betel/alkaloids] The name "alkaloids" (German: *Alkaloide*) was introduced in 1819 by German chemist Carl Friedrich Wilhelm Meissner, and is derived from late Latin root *alkali* and the Greek-language suffix -οειδής -('like').
[src:betel/alkaloids] However, the term came into wide use only after the publication of a review article, by Oscar Jacobsen in the chemical dictionary of Albert Ladenburg in the 1880s.
[src:betel/alkaloids] The name "alkaloid" was introduced, since at the time, chemists conceptualized the category of "alkaline" in such a way that plants cannot produce alkaline.
[src:betel/alkaloids] For instance, potash, an alkaline substance that can be extracted from plants by burning, was thought to be either produced during burning, or extracted by plant from the soil.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Subsequent research by chemists to extract the "principle" (what we nowadays call the active ingredient) of medicinal plants, led to the discovery of various substances that had properties resembling alkalines as understood at the time.
[src:betel/alkaloids] These substances were variously named "salifiable vegetable bases", "vegetable organic compounds", "organic bases", etc.
[src:betel/alkaloids] After enough such substances were discovered, these substances were classified as "alkaloid", a new chemical category.
[src:betel/alkaloids] There is no unique method for naming alkaloids.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Many individual names are formed by adding the suffix "ine" to the species or genus name.
[src:betel/alkaloids] For example, atropine is isolated from the plant *Atropa belladonna*; strychnine is obtained from the seed of the Strychnine tree (*Strychnos nux-vomica* L.).
[src:betel/alkaloids] Where several alkaloids are extracted from one plant their names are often distinguished by variations in the suffix: "idine", "anine", "aline", "inine" etc.
[src:betel/alkaloids] There are also at least 86 alkaloids whose names contain the root "vin" because they are extracted from *vinca* plants such as *Vinca rosea* (*Catharanthus roseus*); these are called *vinca* alkaloids.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Alkaloid-containing plants have been used by humans since ancient times for therapeutic and recreational purposes.
[src:betel/alkaloids] For example, medicinal plants have been known in Mesopotamia from about 2000 BC.
[src:betel/alkaloids] The *Odyssey* of Homer referred to a gift given to Helen by the Egyptian queen, a drug bringing oblivion.
[src:betel/alkaloids] It is believed that the gift was an opium-containing drug.
[src:betel/alkaloids] A Chinese book on houseplants written in 1st–3rd centuries BC mentioned a medical use of ephedra and opium poppies.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Also, coca leaves have been used by Indigenous South Americans since ancient times.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Extracts from plants containing toxic alkaloids, such as aconitine and tubocurarine, were used since antiquity for poisoning arrows.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Studies of alkaloids began in the 19th century.
[src:betel/alkaloids] In 1804, the German chemist Friedrich Sertürner isolated from opium a "soporific principle" (Latin: *principium somniferum*), which he called "morphium", referring to Morpheus, the Greek god of dreams; in German and some other Central-European languages, this is still the name of the drug.
[src:betel/alkaloids] The term "morphine", used in English and French, was given by the French physicist Joseph Louis Gay-Lussac.
[src:betel/alkaloids] A significant contribution to the chemistry of alkaloids in the early years of its development was made by the French researchers Pierre Joseph Pelletier and Joseph Bienaimé Caventou, who discovered quinine (1820) and strychnine (1818).
[src:betel/alkaloids] Several other alkaloids were discovered around that time, including xanthine (1817), atropine (1819), caffeine (1820), coniine (1827), nicotine (1828), colchicine (1833), sparteine (1851), and cocaine (1860).
[src:betel/alkaloids] The development of the chemistry of alkaloids was accelerated by the emergence of spectroscopic and chromatographic methods in the 20th century, so that by 2008 more than 12,000 alkaloids had been identified.
[src:betel/alkaloids] The first complete synthesis of an alkaloid was achieved in 1886 by the German chemist Albert Ladenburg.
[src:betel/alkaloids] He produced coniine by reacting 2-methylpyridine with acetaldehyde and reducing the resulting 2-propenyl pyridine with sodium.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Compared with most other classes of natural compounds, alkaloids are characterized by a great structural diversity.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Initially, when knowledge of chemical structures was lacking, botanical classification of the source plants was relied on.
[src:betel/alkaloids] This classification is now considered obsolete.
[src:betel/alkaloids] More recent classifications are based on similarity of the carbon skeleton (*e.g.*, indole-, isoquinoline-, and pyridine-like) or biochemical precursor (ornithine, lysine, tyrosine, tryptophan, etc.).
[src:betel/alkaloids] However, they require compromises in borderline cases; for example, nicotine contains a pyridine fragment from nicotinamide and a pyrrolidine part from ornithine and therefore can be assigned to both classes.
[src:betel/alkaloids] "Protoalkaloids", which contain nitrogen (but not the nitrogen heterocycle) and also originate from amino acids.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Examples include mescaline, adrenaline and ephedrine.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Polyamine alkaloids – derivatives of putrescine, spermidine, and spermine.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Pseudoalkaloids – alkaloid-like compounds that do not originate from amino acids.
[src:betel/alkaloids] This group includes terpene-like and steroid-like alkaloids, as well as purine-like alkaloids such as caffeine, theobromine, theacrine and theophylline.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Some authors classify ephedrine and cathinone as pseudoalkaloids.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Those originate from the amino acid phenylalanine, but acquire their nitrogen atom not from the amino acid but through transamination.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Some alkaloids do not have the carbon skeleton characteristic of their group.
[src:betel/alkaloids] So, galanthamine and homoaporphines do not contain isoquinoline fragment, but are, in general, attributed to isoquinoline alkaloids.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Most alkaloids contain oxygen in their molecular structure; those compounds are usually colorless crystals at ambient conditions.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Oxygen-free alkaloids, such as nicotine or coniine, are typically volatile, colorless, oily liquids.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Some alkaloids are colored, like berberine (yellow) and sanguinarine (orange).
[src:betel/alkaloids] Most alkaloids are weak bases, but some, such as theobromine and theophylline, are amphoteric.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Many alkaloids dissolve poorly in water but readily dissolve in organic solvents, such as diethyl ether, chloroform or 1,2-dichloroethane.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Caffeine, cocaine, codeine and nicotine are slightly soluble in water (with a solubility of ≥1g/L), whereas others, including morphine and yohimbine are very slightly water-soluble (0.1–1 g/L).
[src:betel/alkaloids] Alkaloids and acids form salts of various strengths.
[src:betel/alkaloids] These salts are usually freely soluble in water and ethanol and poorly soluble in most organic solvents.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Exceptions include scopolamine hydrobromide, which is soluble in organic solvents, and the water-soluble quinine sulfate.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Most alkaloids have a bitter taste or are poisonous when ingested.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Alkaloid production in plants appeared to have evolved in response to feeding by herbivorous animals; however, some animals have evolved the ability to detoxify alkaloids.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Some alkaloids can produce developmental defects in the offspring of animals that consume but cannot detoxify the alkaloids.
[src:betel/alkaloids] One example is the alkaloid cyclopamine, produced in the leaves of corn lily.
[src:betel/alkaloids] During the 1950s, up to 25% of lambs born by sheep that had grazed on corn lily had serious facial deformations.
[src:betel/alkaloids] These ranged from deformed jaws to cyclopia.
[src:betel/alkaloids] After decades of research, in the 1980s, the compound responsible for these deformities was identified as the alkaloid 11-deoxyjervine, later renamed to cyclopamine.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Alkaloids are generated by various living organisms, especially by higher plants – about 10 to 25% of those contain alkaloids.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Therefore, in the past the term "alkaloid" was associated with plants.
[src:betel/alkaloids] The alkaloids content in plants is usually within a few percent and is inhomogeneous over the plant tissues.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Depending on the type of plants, the maximum concentration is observed in the leaves (for example, black henbane), fruits or seeds (Strychnine tree), root (*Rauvolfia serpentina*) or bark (cinchona).
[src:betel/alkaloids] Furthermore, different tissues of the same plants may contain different alkaloids.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Beside plants, alkaloids are found in certain types of fungus, such as psilocybin in the fruiting bodies of the genus *Psilocybe*, and in animals, such as bufotenin in the skin of some toads and a number of insects, markedly ants.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Many marine organisms also contain alkaloids.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Some amines, such as adrenaline and serotonin, which play an important role in higher animals, are similar to alkaloids in their structure and biosynthesis and are sometimes called alkaloids.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Because of the structural diversity of alkaloids, there is no single method of their extraction from natural raw materials.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Most methods exploit the property of most alkaloids to be soluble in organic solvents but not in water, and the opposite tendency of their salts.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Their mixture is extracted first and then individual alkaloids are separated.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Plants are thoroughly ground before extraction.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Most alkaloids are present in the raw plants in the form of salts of organic acids.
[src:betel/alkaloids] The extracted alkaloids may remain salts or change into bases.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Base extraction is achieved by processing the raw material with alkaline solutions and extracting the alkaloid bases with organic solvents, such as 1,2-dichloroethane, chloroform, diethyl ether or benzene.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Then, the impurities are dissolved by weak acids; this converts alkaloid bases into salts that are washed away with water.
[src:betel/alkaloids] If necessary, an aqueous solution of alkaloid salts is again made alkaline and treated with an organic solvent.
[src:betel/alkaloids] The process is repeated until the desired purity is achieved.
[src:betel/alkaloids] In the acidic extraction, the raw plant material is processed by a weak acidic solution (*e.g.*, acetic acid in water, ethanol, or methanol).
[src:betel/alkaloids] A base is then added to convert alkaloids to basic forms that are extracted with organic solvent (if the extraction was performed with alcohol, it is removed first, and the remainder is dissolved in water).
[src:betel/alkaloids] The solution is purified as described above.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Alkaloids are separated from their mixture using their different solubility in certain solvents and different reactivity with certain reagents or by distillation.
[src:betel/alkaloids] A number of alkaloids are identified from insects, among which the fire ant venom alkaloids known as solenopsins have received greater attention from researchers.
[src:betel/alkaloids] These insect alkaloids can be efficiently extracted by solvent immersion of live fire ants or by centrifugation of live ants followed by silica-gel chromatography purification.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Tracking and dosing the extracted solenopsin ant alkaloids has been described as possible based on their absorbance peak around 232 nanometers.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Biological precursors of most alkaloids are amino acids, such as ornithine, lysine, phenylalanine, tyrosine, tryptophan, histidine, aspartic acid, and anthranilic acid.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Nicotinic acid can be synthesized from tryptophan or aspartic acid.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Ways of alkaloid biosynthesis are too numerous and cannot be easily classified.
[src:betel/alkaloids] However, there are a few typical reactions involved in the biosynthesis of various classes of alkaloids, including synthesis of Schiff bases and Mannich reaction.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Schiff bases can be obtained by reacting amines with ketones or aldehydes.
[src:betel/alkaloids] These reactions are a common method of producing C=N bonds.
[src:betel/alkaloids] An integral component of the Mannich reaction, in addition to an amine and a carbonyl compound, is a carbanion, which plays the role of the nucleophile in the nucleophilic addition to the ion formed by the reaction of the amine and the carbonyl.
[src:betel/alkaloids] In addition to the described above monomeric alkaloids, there are also dimeric, and even trimeric and tetrameric alkaloids formed upon condensation of two, three, and four monomeric alkaloids.
[src:betel/alkaloids] There are also dimeric alkaloids formed from two distinct monomers, such as the *vinca* alkaloids vinblastine and vincristine, which are formed from the coupling of catharanthine and vindoline.
[src:betel/alkaloids] The newer semi-synthetic chemotherapeutic agent vinorelbine is used in the treatment of non-small-cell lung cancer.
[src:betel/alkaloids] It is another derivative dimer of vindoline and catharanthine and is synthesised from anhydrovinblastine, starting either from leurosine or the monomers themselves.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Alkaloids are among the most important and best-known secondary metabolites, i.e. biogenic substances not directly involved in the normal growth, development, or reproduction of the organism.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Instead, they generally mediate ecological interactions, which may produce a selective advantage for the organism by increasing its survivability or fecundity.
[src:betel/alkaloids] In some cases their function, if any, remains unclear.
[src:betel/alkaloids] An early hypothesis, that alkaloids are the final products of nitrogen metabolism in plants, as urea and uric acid are in mammals, was refuted by the finding that their concentration fluctuates rather than steadily increasing.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Most of the known functions of alkaloids are related to protection.
[src:betel/alkaloids] For example, aporphine alkaloid liriodenine produced by the tulip tree protects it from parasitic mushrooms.
[src:betel/alkaloids] In addition, the presence of alkaloids in the plant prevents insects and chordate animals from eating it.
[src:betel/alkaloids] However, some animals are adapted to alkaloids and even use them in their own metabolism.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Such alkaloid-related substances as serotonin, dopamine and histamine are important neurotransmitters in animals.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Alkaloids are also known to regulate plant growth.
[src:betel/alkaloids] One example of an organism that uses alkaloids for protection is the *Utetheisa ornatrix*, more commonly known as the ornate moth.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Pyrrolizidine alkaloids render these larvae and adult moths unpalatable to many of their natural enemies like coccinelid beetles, green lacewings, insectivorous hemiptera and insectivorous bats.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Another example of alkaloids being utilized occurs in the poison hemlock moth (*Agonopterix alstroemeriana).* This moth feeds on its highly toxic and alkaloid-rich host plant poison hemlock (*Conium maculatum*) during its larval stage.
[src:betel/alkaloids] *A. alstroemeriana* may benefit twofold from the toxicity of the naturally occurring alkaloids, both through the unpalatability of the species to predators and through the ability of *A. alstroemeriana* to recognize *Conium maculatum* as the correct location for oviposition.
[src:betel/alkaloids] A fire ant venom alkaloid known as solenopsin has been demonstrated to protect queens of invasive fire ants during the foundation of new nests, thus playing a central role in the spread of this pest ant species around the world.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Medical use of alkaloid-containing plants has a long history, and, thus, when the first alkaloids were isolated in the 19th century, they immediately found application in clinical practice.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Many synthetic and semisynthetic drugs are structural modifications of the alkaloids, which were designed to enhance or change the primary effect of the drug and reduce unwanted side-effects.
[src:betel/alkaloids] For example, naloxone, an opioid receptor antagonist, is a derivative of thebaine that is present in opium.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Prior to the development of a wide range of relatively low-toxic synthetic pesticides, some alkaloids, such as salts of nicotine and anabasine, were used as insecticides.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Their use was limited by their high toxicity to humans.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Preparations of plants and fungi containing alkaloids and their extracts, and later pure alkaloids, have long been used as psychoactive substances.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Cocaine, caffeine, and cathinone are stimulants of the central nervous system.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Mescaline and many indole alkaloids (such as psilocybin, dimethyltryptamine and ibogaine) have hallucinogenic effect.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Morphine and codeine are strong narcotic pain killers.
[src:betel/alkaloids] There are alkaloids that do not have strong psychoactive effect themselves, but are precursors for semi-synthetic psychoactive drugs.
[src:betel/alkaloids] For example, ephedrine and pseudoephedrine are used to produce methcathinone and methamphetamine.
[src:betel/alkaloids] Thebaine is used in the synthesis of many painkillers such as oxycodone.
[src:betel/allanblackia-oil] Currently, *Allanblackia* seeds are harvested in the wild to produce the oil, but these producers cannot produce enough oil to meet market demand.
[src:betel/allanblackia-oil] Finding sustainable ways to increase production could bring many social, environmental, and economic benefits to the communities which produce *Allanblackia*.
[src:betel/allanblackia-oil] To ensure increased production is sustainable and benefits the communities growing the trees, a number of organizations have collaborated to develop a set of standards and methods as guidelines for increasing *Allanblackia* production.
[src:betel/allanblackia-oil] Other organizations are working to establish tree nurseries and other sustainable means of domesticating *Allanblackia*.
[src:betel/allanblackia-oil] Allanblackia oil is an edible vegetable oil derived from the seeds from the fruits of *Allanblackia* trees.
[src:betel/allanblackia-oil] This is an evergreen tree producing big brown fruits.
[src:betel/allanblackia-oil] Inside those fruits are the seeds that contain the allanblackia oil.
[src:betel/allanblackia-oil] The genus *Allanblackia*, which belongs to the family Clusiaceae, consists of nine (possibly ten) tree species, all restricted to Africa.
[src:betel/allanblackia-oil] All members of the genus are dioecious (having separate male and female trees).
[src:betel/allanblackia-oil] There are nine published species of *Allanblackia*, mostly very similar to each other.
[src:betel/allanblackia-oil] *Allanblackia* trees are commonly found in the wet tropical rain belt of West, Central and East Africa (from Sierra Leone to Tanzania).
[src:betel/allanblackia-oil] They grow primarily in tropical rainforests, but can also be found on cultivated farmland areas.
[src:betel/allanblackia-oil] These species occur in moist low-land areas (*A. parviflora*, *A. floribunda*) or upland rain forests (*A. stuhlmannii*).
[src:betel/allanblackia-oil] The genus *Allanblackia* was named in honour of the botanist Allan Black.
[src:betel/allanblackia-oil] He was the first curator of Kew Gardens and was responsible for the private collection of Charles Darwin.
[src:betel/allanblackia-oil] Very respected amongst his peers, he died at a young age aboard ship off the Cocos Islands in the Bay of Bengal and the genus *Allanblackia* was named in his memory.
[src:betel/allanblackia-oil] The name of *Allanblackia* trees used by the indigenous people in Tanzania is actually *msambu* or *mkimbo* in Swahili or sometimes *mkani* (*mkanyi*, *mkany*) in local languages.
[src:betel/allanblackia-oil] In Nigeria area of River State the local name used is *obiobo obo*.
[src:betel/allanblackia-oil] A key characteristic is that the fatty acids are organized into a two main triglycerides.
[src:betel/allanblackia-oil] These are called 1,3-distearoyl-2-oleoyl-glycerol (abbreviated as SOS at an average level of 69%) and 1,2-dioleoyl-3-stearoyl-sn-glycerol (abbreviated as sn-SOO at an average level of 23%).
[src:betel/allanblackia-oil] This simple triglyceride composition provides *Allanblackia* seed oil with very steep melting behavior.
[src:betel/allanblackia-oil] This composition makes it useful for making food products such as margarine, without any further modification like fractionation of fractional crystallization.
[src:betel/allanblackia-oil] Specific physical characteristics of SOS-SOO mixtures, like fat crystallization aspects, have extensively been investigated in model systems.
[src:betel/allanblackia-oil] The volumes of Allanblackia seeds, and hence seed oil, produced until now very low.
[src:betel/allanblackia-oil] The volume of allanblackia seed oil is in the range of 100 metric tonnes per annum only.
[src:betel/allanblackia-oil] These volumes are generated by wild-harvesting mainly done by collectors in Tanzania.
[src:betel/allanblackia-oil] When initial studies on the potential of wild-harvesting were done in the early 2000s, the expectations were very high predicting annual production of up to 40,000 tonnes of seeds.
[src:betel/allanblackia-oil] In reality only a few tonnes of seeds were harvested in the first year as the number of wild Allanblackia trees that could actually be harvested had severely been overestimated.
[src:betel/allanblackia-oil] Through the plantation of the tree with local farmers in Tanzania, Ghana and Nigeria, the production volumes are expected to increase in the coming decade, once these trees are old enough to starting producing fruits and big enough to carry more of the large fruit pods.
[src:betel/allanblackia-oil] Increasing the volumes obviously must be done sustainably and hence socio-economic and environmental aspects are being looked at.
[src:betel/allanblackia-oil] For example, the value of Allanblackia as a new cash (annual) crop for Africa means training of local communities not to cut Allanblackia trees for use as timber and firewood.
[src:betel/allanblackia-oil] But doing so is also a means of helping to conserve local biodiversity.
[src:betel/allanblackia-oil] The Union for Ethical Biotrade (UEBT) has developed a standard and a verification framework against which the sustainability of the Allanblackia supply chain can be audited and approved.
[src:betel/allanblackia-oil] UEBT is a member of the International Social and Environmental Accreditation and Labelling Alliance, which promotes sustainability standards.
[src:betel/allanblackia-oil] Wild harvesting as a production method is limited because there are not enough trees to satisfy demand and Allanblackia's flowering and fruiting behavior is erratic.
[src:betel/allanblackia-oil] Since 2006, Novel Development Tanzania has been involved in a domestication program together with the World Agroforestry Centre to domesticate the species using participatory tree domestication approach.
[src:betel/allanblackia-oil] The program includes community sensitization, exploration, participatory selections of superior mother trees, conservation in field gene banks, development of agroforestry systems with Allanblackia and market development.
[src:betel/allanblackia-oil] Secondly, the program consists of developing asexual and sexual propagation protocols, which are necessary to overcome challenges in multiplication such as seed dormancy, long juvenile phase and high variability of desired traits.
[src:betel/allanblackia-oil] The domestication program of Allanblackia through public-private partnership and participatory tree domestication could serve as a model for domestication of other underutilized African tree species of high economic potential.
[src:betel/allanblackia-oil] In Tanzania the use of allanblackia seed oil goes back almost a century.
[src:betel/allanblackia-oil] It has been reported that during the First World War allanblackia oil was already tested as a cocoa butter alternative.
[src:betel/allanblackia-oil] Also in the seventies the such application was again explored in Europe.
[src:betel/allanblackia-oil] However the application never hit the market because larger volumes of the oil were simply not available due to the lack of an organized supply chain.
[src:betel/allanblackia-oil] Nowadays there is still in hardly any local use of Allanblackia seed oil as people prefer use of easily available liquid oils and cheap industrial soaps.
[src:betel/allanblackia-oil] The allanblackia tree has predominantly been used for timber in the last decades and hence the number of trees has significantly reduced .
[src:betel/allanblackia-oil] Most of the allanblackia trees nowadays remaining in the wild are growing in the East Usambara Mountains which provides the right climate for this tree.
[src:betel/allanblackia-oil] As a result, even today the volumes of oil available from wild-harvesting are still very small.
[src:betel/allanblackia-oil] The major application potential identified today is in the use as a structuring fat to produce low-trans margarines and dairy cream alternatives, and as cocoa butter equivalent in confectionery applications.
[src:betel/allanblackia-oil] In the European Union as of December 2014, all different types of vegetable oils will be listed on the ingredient label of food products using those ingredients.
[src:betel/allanblackia-oil] Recently Allanblackia seed oil was introduced in margarine and can be found as such on the product ingredient list.
[src:betel/allium-bisceptrum] The twincrest onion is a perennial at altitudes ranging from 2000 to 2900 meters.
[src:betel/allium-bisceptrum] It grows to between ten and forty cm high.
[src:betel/allium-bisceptrum] The onion bulbs are round and egg-shaped.
[src:betel/allium-bisceptrum] The bulbs have a light tint and when cut, have a powerful odor.
[src:betel/allium-bisceptrum] The flower heads are about 10–15 mm in length.
[src:betel/allium-bisceptrum] The flowers are varying shades of purple or pink.
[src:betel/allium-bisceptrum] Each flower head contains six sharply pointed tepals and often a darker stripe.
[src:betel/allium-bisceptrum] Their long, flat leaves usually come in pairs of two, stay green longer than for most other onions, and give off an odor when scratched.
[src:betel/allium-bisceptrum] In California, *A. bisceptrum* is distributed throughout the counties of Alpine, El Dorado, Glenn, Inyo, Lassen, Mendocino, Mono, Modoc, Mariposa, Nevada, Plumas, San Bernardino, San Diego, Shasta, Sierra, Trinity, Tulare, and Tuolumne.
[src:betel/allium-bisceptrum] It is also widely distributed in Nevada, Utah, Arizona, southeastern Oregon, and southern Idaho with isolated populations reported from northern Idaho and from southeastern Washington (Franklin County).
[src:betel/allium-bisceptrum] Twincrest onions grow at high elevations and thrive in the cold.
[src:betel/allium-bisceptrum] Their seeds can be planted outdoors in the early fall.
[src:betel/allium-bisceptrum] They do not need to be warmed throughout the winter.
[src:betel/allium-bisceptrum] In fact, in warmer winters, the plants may need to be kept at lower temperatures to insure growth and germination.
[src:betel/allium-bisceptrum] Their seeds should be planted in a nice and dense model with around four to five seeds per square foot of soil.
[src:betel/allium-bisceptrum] Watering early on is not necessary unless extremely dry.
[src:betel/allium-bisceptrum] Rain water should be enough to keep the plant alive until germination in the spring.
[src:betel/allium-bisceptrum] When spring time arrives, two inches of water a week should be administered.
[src:betel/allium-bisceptrum] If watered correctly, wild onions will begin to grow.
[src:betel/allium-bisceptrum] They can grow in the sunlight, but they prefer the shade.
[src:betel/allium-bisceptrum] It is necessary to keep the soil nice and moist, but not too wet because these growing onion bulbs do not have enough reserves to keep the plant alive.
[src:betel/allium-bisceptrum] Watering should be discontinued as soon as yellow foliage begins to appear.
[src:betel/allium-bisceptrum] At this point, the plant should be ready to mature and flower on its own.
[src:betel/allium-bisceptrum] At least three to five years should be expected for this plant to reach a flowering size.
[src:betel/allium-bisceptrum] The bulbs and bulblets of the twincrest onion may be planted as well.
[src:betel/allium-bisceptrum] Maturity and flowering may come quicker planting by bulbs than planting by seeds.
[src:betel/allium-bisceptrum] To do so, bulbs must be picked from the mature wild onion plant.
[src:betel/allium-bisceptrum] These bulbs must then be stored in a dry environment (paper bags with dry peat moss is ideal).
[src:betel/allium-bisceptrum] Late fall, when the first frost comes, is the best time to plant these bulbs.
[src:betel/allium-bisceptrum] These bulbs should be planted in an acidic potting soil with sand and humus for good drainage.
[src:betel/allium-bisceptrum] Daughter bulblets may be planted next to mature bulbs to keep the dense pattern.
[src:betel/allium-bisceptrum] Maintenance must be in order to make sure these bulbs do not receive too much water.
[src:betel/allium-bisceptrum] These bulbs will germinate on their own in the spring time.
[src:betel/allium-bisceptrum] When germination begins in the spring, water must be administered at least once a week.
[src:betel/allium-bisceptrum] If it is a dry and rainless week, water should be administered twice that week.
[src:betel/allium-bisceptrum] Adding a liquid fertilizer may increase growth and vigor.
[src:betel/allium-bisceptrum] When flowering occurs, watering may be ceased.
[src:betel/allium-bisceptrum] While harvesting, the Washoe keep some of the plants intact so the plant will continue to seed.
[src:betel/allium-bisceptrum] They also do not uproot the bulbs so plants will continue to grow year after year.
[src:betel/allium-bisceptrum] The twincrest onion is still used today by many native Americans including the Nevada Northern Paiute, Gosiute, Northern Ute, and Washoe.
[src:betel/allium-bisceptrum] The Washoe use the leaves and greens of this plant as a spice and flavor their foods.
[src:betel/allium-bisceptrum] They pick out the young leaves and stems of the plant after the last of the snow melts in early spring.
[src:betel/allium-bisceptrum] These young leaves and stems, which are only inches from the ground are the most delectable as their flavors range from mild to strong.
[src:betel/allium-bisceptrum] The Washoe sometimes pray before picking these leaves in hopes of a good harvesting year.
[src:betel/allium-bisceptrum] These leaves are similar to chives bought from supermarkets.
[src:betel/allium-bisceptrum] These leaves can be used in various culinary forms, whether eaten raw, or stir fried with meats and other vegetables.
[src:betel/allium-bisceptrum] Wild animals in the area such as elk, black bears, white-tailed prairie dogs, and mantled ground squirrels eat the bulbs of the wild onions.
[src:betel/allium-bisceptrum] Some cattle and sheep also graze these plants.
[src:betel/allium-canadense] Crow garlic (*Allium vineale*) is similar, but it has a strong garlic taste.
[src:betel/allium-canadense] The narrow, grass-like leaves originate near the base of the stem, which is topped by a dome-like cluster of star-shaped, pink or white flowers.
[src:betel/allium-canadense] These flowers may be partially or entirely replaced by bulblets.
[src:betel/allium-canadense] When present, the flowers are hermaphroditic (both male and female organs) and are pollinated by American bees (not honeybees) and other insects.
[src:betel/allium-canadense] It typically flowers in the spring and early summer, from May to June.
[src:betel/allium-canadense] The bulblet-producing form is classified as *A. canadense* var.
[src:betel/allium-canadense] It was once thought that the tree onion could be related to this plant, but it is now known that the cultivated tree onion is a hybrid between the common onion (*A. cepa*) and Welsh onion (*A. fistulosum*), classified as *A.* × *proliferum*.
[src:betel/allium-canadense] The Canada onion is cultivated as a vegetable in home gardens in Cuba, scattered locally in the south to western parts of the island.
[src:betel/allium-canadense] It was formerly collected from the wild to be eaten by Native Americans and by European settlers.
[src:betel/allium-canadense] People in the Cherokee Nation and Chickasaw Nation continue the tradition of picking and cooking wild onions in early spring.
[src:betel/allium-canadense] Various Native American tribes also used the plant for other purposes: for example, rubbing the plant on the body for protection from insect, lizard, scorpion, and tarantula bites.
[src:betel/allium-canadense] The whole plant can be eaten raw, with the tougher outer layers removed.
[src:betel/allium-canadense] It can also be cooked and included in any recipe calling for onions.
[src:betel/allium-canadense] However, there have been reported cases of poisoning when deathcamas bulbs were mistaken for wild onions.
[src:betel/allium-canadense] Additionally, long term consumption of wild onion bulbs reduces iodine uptake by the thyroid gland.
[src:betel/allium-canadense] This can worsen iodine deficiency for people with a diet that is low in iodine.
[src:betel/allium-canadense] Horses are vulnerable to developing hemolytic anemia from eating wild onion leaves.
[src:betel/betel] The term betel was derived from the Malayalam/Tamil word *vettila* via Portuguese.
[src:betel/betel] The betel leaf is cultivated mostly in the Indian subcontinent and Southeast Asia, from India to Papua New Guinea.
[src:betel/betel] It needs a compatible tree or a long pole for support.
[src:betel/betel] Betel requires well-drained fertile soil.
[src:betel/betel] Waterlogged, saline and alkali soils are unsuitable for its cultivation.
[src:betel/betel] In Bangladesh, farmers called *barui* prepare a garden called a *barouj* in which to grow betel.
[src:betel/betel] The *barouj* is fenced with bamboo sticks and coconut leaves.
[src:betel/betel] The soil is plowed into furrows of 10 to 15 m length, 75 cm in width and 75 cm depth.
[src:betel/betel] Oil cakes, manure, and leaves are thoroughly incorporated with the topsoil of the furrows and wood ash.
[src:betel/betel] The cuttings are planted at the beginning of the monsoon season.
[src:betel/betel] Proper shade and irrigation are essential for the successful cultivation of this crop.
[src:betel/betel] Betel needs constantly moist soil, but there should not be excessive moisture.
[src:betel/betel] Irrigation is frequent and light, and standing water should not remain for more than half an hour.
[src:betel/betel] Dried leaves and wood ash are applied to the furrows at fortnightly intervals and cow dung slurry is sprinkled.
[src:betel/betel] Application of different kinds of leaves at monthly intervals is believed advantageous for the growth of the betel.
[src:betel/betel] In three to six months, the vines reach 150 to 180 cm (59 to 71 in) in height, and they will branch.
[src:betel/betel] Harvest begins with the farmer plucking the leaf and its petiole with his right thumb.
[src:betel/betel] The betel plant has made its way to research labs of many Bangladesh chemical and food nutrition companies.
[src:betel/betel] The harvested leaves are consumed locally and exported to other parts of Asia, the Middle East, Europe, and the Americas.
[src:betel/betel] Betel is grown and cultivated as an important crop in rural Bangladesh.
[src:betel/betel] The primary use of betel leaf is as a wrapper for the chewing of areca nut, or in modern times, tobacco, where it is mainly used to add flavour.
[src:betel/betel] The practice is thought to have originated in the Philippines around 5,000 years ago, where — to date — the oldest remains of areca nuts and calcium from crushed sea shells have been found in the Duyong Cave archaeological site.
[src:betel/betel] It spread along with the Austronesian migrations to the rest of Southeast Asia, Taiwan, South China, and South Asia.
[src:betel/betel] It is unknown when or why betel leaves were first combined with areca nuts, since areca nuts can be chewed alone.
[src:betel/betel] While the practice of chewing betel leaf existed even before the common era, with attested references from at least the 3rd century CE, the ingredient mix (paan/betel quid) it was chewed with changed over time.
[src:betel/betel] Areca nut, calcium hydroxide and catechu were the historic ingredients, as referenced in texts from 9th century CE.
[src:betel/betel] Tobacco started to feature in the 20th century.
[src:betel/betel] The practice of chewing betel leaf is on the decline, and now quid consisting of tobacco, areca nut, and limewater, known as gutka, is more popular.
[src:betel/betel] In India and Sri Lanka, a sheaf of betel leaves is traditionally offered as a mark of respect and auspicious beginnings.
[src:betel/betel] Occasions include greeting elders at wedding ceremonies, celebrating the New Year, and offering payment to physicians and astrologers, to whom money and/or areca nut, placed on top of the sheaf of leaves, are offered in thanks for blessings.
[src:betel/betel] In Bengali weddings, the bride is brought to the groom, seated on a platform and her face covered in betel leaves.
[src:betel/betel] In Papua New Guinea and the Solomon Islands, the inflorescence stalk of the betel tree, known as *daka* or "mustard stick", is consumed together with the leaves.
[src:betel/betel] It may also be used in cooking, usually raw, for its peppery taste.
[src:betel/betel] Use of *binlang*, or betel, has over a 300-year history in areas of China, where it was once promoted for medicinal use.
[src:betel/betel] Red betel leaf is sometimes used as an antibacterial mouthwash.
[src:betel/betel] While chewing or consuming betel leaf on its own has no known negative effect and have been shown to be chemopreventive in animal models, it is most often used to wrap *betel quid* for chewing, which also contains the carcinogenic and mildly narcotic areca nut.
[src:betel/betel] Habitual use of this popular product (sometimes inaccurately referred to as "betel nut") damages the oral cavity and is associated with a wide range of adverse systemic health effects, including harm to the cardiovascular and central nervous systems.
[src:betel/betel] Chewing paan (betel quid) is strongly associated with a higher risk of developing head and neck cancer, as well as oropharyngeal squamous cell carcinoma (OPSCC), a form of cancer that affects the mouth, tonsils, and throat.
[src:betel/betel] Multiple studies demonstrate that betel quid without added tobacco also causes esophageal cancer, and in some instances, liver cancer.
[src:betel/betel] Betel quid chewing can also cause stillbirth, premature birth, and low birth weight.
[src:betel/betel] The International Agency for Research on Cancer (IARC) and the World Health Organization (WHO) accept the scientific evidence that chewing tobacco and areca nut is carcinogenic to humans.
[src:betel/betel] As with chewing tobacco, chewing betel quid is discouraged by preventive healthcare efforts.
[src:betel/betel] While various scales exist to measure betel quid dependency, more comprehensive and validated tools are needed to assess this dependency effectively across different populations.
[src:betel/betel] Chemistry of betel leaf varies geographically and is mostly chavibetol dominant.
[src:betel/betel] Safrole is a major component of Sri Lankan *Piper betle*.
[src:betel/betel] Eugenol, isoeugenol, and germacrene D are other dominant compounds in other chemotypes.
[src:betel/betel] Leaves also contain eugenol, chavicol, hydroxychavicol, and caryophyllene.
[src:betel/betel] Stems contain phytosterols (β-sitosterol, β-daucosterol, stigmasterol etc.), alkaloids (piperine, pellitorine, piperdardine, guineensine etc.), lignan (pinoresinol) and other components.
[src:betel/betel] Some of them are oleanolic acid, dehydropipernonaline, piperolein-B, bornyl *cis*-4-hydroxycinnamate and bornyl *p*-coumarate.
[src:betel/betel] Roots contain aristololactam A-II, a phenylpropene, 4-allyl resorcinol and a diketosteroid stigmast-4-en-3,6-dione.
[src:betel/betel] Its essential oil consists of 50 different compounds, of which major components are eugenol, caryophyllene, terpinolene, terpinene, cadinene, and 3-carene.
[src:betel/betel] Betel vines are cultivated throughout southeast Asia, in plots typically 20 to 2,000 square metres (0.005 to 0.5 acre) in size.
[src:betel/betel] Malaysian farmers cultivate four types of betel plants: sirih India, sirih Melayu, sirih Cina and sirih Udang.
[src:betel/betel] The harvest is then sold in bundles of leaves, each bundle costing in 2011 between MYR 0.30 and 0.50 ($0.07 and $0.12).
[src:betel/betel] In Sri Lanka, betel is grown all over the country.
[src:betel/betel] Commercial production of betel, with bigger leaves with dark green colour combined with thickness, known as "kalu bulath", is confined to a few districts, such as Kurunagala, Gampaha, Kegalle, Kalutara and Colombo.
[src:betel/betel] These are sold at a wholesaler in lots of 1,000 leaves.
[src:betel/betel] According to a report published by the United Nations Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO), a successful betel farm in Sri Lanka can provide a supplemental income to a farmer by providing six days of work every six months and net income when the leaf prices are attractive.
[src:betel/betel] The FAO study found the successful farm's yield to be 18,000 leaves per 150 square feet (14 m2).
[src:betel/betel] The additional salary and income to the Sri Lankan betel grower, assuming he or she provides all needed labor and keeps all net profit, is SL Rs.
[src:betel/betel] 1635 per 150 square feet (14 m2) of betel farm every 6 months ($90 per "decimal" per year, or $9000 per acre per year).
[src:betel/betel] If the farmer hires outside labor to tend the betel vines and harvest the crop, the net income to the betel farm owner was SL Rs.
[src:betel/betel] 735 per 150 square feet (14 m2) of betel farm every six months ($40 per decimal per year, or $4000 per acre per year).
[src:betel/betel] The market prices for betel leaves vary with the wet and dry seasons in Sri Lanka, and in 2010 averaged SL Rs.
[src:betel/betel] The FAO study assumes no losses from erratic weather and no losses during storage and transportation of perishable betel leaves.
[src:betel/betel] These losses are usually between 35% and 70%.
[src:betel/betel] In Bangladesh, betel leaf farming yields vary by region and vine variety.
[src:betel/betel] In one region where betel leaf cultivation is the main source of income for farmers, a total of 2,825 hectares of land is dedicated to betel vine farming.
[src:betel/betel] The average production costs for these betel farms in Bangladesh are about Tk 300,000 per hectare ($4,000 per hectare, $16 per decimal).
[src:betel/betel] The farm owners can earn a profit of over Tk 100,000 per hectare ($1,334 per hectare, $5.34 per decimal).
[src:betel/betel] In India, a 2006 research reported betel vines being cultivated on about 55,000 hectares of farmland, with an annual production worth of about IN Rs.
[src:betel/betel] The betel farming industry, the report claims, supports about 400,000 – 500,000 agricultural families.
[src:betel/betel] A March 2011 report claims that betel farming is on a decline in India.
[src:betel/betel] While in ideal conditions some farms may gross annual incomes after expenses of over IN Rs.
[src:betel/betel] 26,000 per 10 decimal farm ($5,780 per acre), a betel farm's income is highly erratic from year to year, due to varying rainfall patterns, temperature, and spoilage rates of 35% to 70% during transport over poor infrastructure.
[src:betel/betel] Simultaneously, the demand for betel leaves has been dropping in India due to acceptance of gutkha (chewing tobacco) by consumers over betel leaf-based ‘‘paan’’ preparation.
[src:betel/betel] The report cites betel leaf trading has dropped by 65% from 2000 to 2010 and created an oversupply.
[src:betel/betel] As a result, the report claims Indian farmers do not find betel farming lucrative anymore.
